3) any coverage of the issues around data integrity within the air should focus on all hcps, not just those who were examined in the latest piece of work

despite all of these issues with the editorialisation of the study, there remains some points that are important 1) all immunising-hcps should be engaging with air 2) this should be done prior to and after a vaccination, to ensure records are correct
in fact, in some pharmacy models, pharmacists have not been the vaccinator until this season (2019/2020) so vaccines provided in pharmacy ≠ vaccines provided by pharmacists

there is also an interesting reliance on claims made by peak bodies & banner groups about number of vaccines provided in pharmacy ie all claims of vaccination in pharmacy must have been provided by a pharmacist...... but this is not the case.
the discussion leans heavily on the idea that these are errors or practicing outside of scope, and don't dwell on any other cause for this data to exist (which are more likely to be the answer....)

for instance, pharmacists have uploaded data to air for immunisations that they are not able to initiate without a prescription. the authors assume that this is either an error, that pharmacists are acting outside of scope, or that pharmacists are uploading data for other hcps

the data is quite rigorous, but the editorialisation is interesting. if you read through  other reports, you will see that uptake of air is traditionally slow, and that vaccination recording by all health professionals is low there is also some unusual assumptions made...
